<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910813-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>910813-0023.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Magma Power Co.:   Concern Sets Tentative Pact   On 25-Year Power Purchase</HL><DATE>08/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   MGMA</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Magma Power Co. said it reached a tentative agreement on a25-year power purchase agreement with California's ImperialIrrigation District. Under the agreement, Magma would expandthe capacity of three Salton Sea geothermal power plants, andsell up to 18 megawatts of electricity an hour to thedistrict.   The pact calls for San Diego-based Magma to make aninitial $19.8 million investment in the expansion, saidWallace Dieckmann, vice president and controller. Uponcompletion of the expansion, expected June 1, 1992, theproject should increase annual revenue about $4.5 million,Mr. Dieckmann said. Magma's annual revenue is about $95million.</LP><TEXT>   The operator of geothermal resources currently owns a 50%stake in four Salton Sea geothermal power plants, whichgenerate more than 160 megawatts an hour. It also owns morethan 47,000 acres of geothermal leases in California andNevada.   The irrigation district supplies water to Imperial Valleyand power to Imperial and Coachella Valleys, including therapidly growing area south of Palm Springs, Calif.</TEXT></DOC>